SIMPLE: spell
RECORDS: 6

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Spell
<hw>Spell</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>speld</ets>,
AS. <ets>speld</ets> a spill to light a candle with; akin to D.
<ets>speld</ets> a pin, OD. <ets>spelle</ets>, G. <ets>spalten</ets> to
split, OHG. <ets>spaltan</ets>, MHG. <ets>spelte</ets> a splinter, Icel.
<ets>spjald</ets> a square tablet, Goth. <ets>spilda</ets> a writing
tablet. Cf. <er>Spill</er>splinter, roll of paper, <er>Spell</er> to
tell the letters of.]</ety> <def>A spelk, or splinter.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Holland.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spell</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Spell
<hw>Spell</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Spelled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Spelling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>spelian</ets> to
supply another's place.]</ety> <def>To supply the place of for a time;
to take the turn of, at work; to relieve; <as>as, to <ex>spell</ex> the
helmsman</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spell</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Spell
<hw>Spell</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The relief of one person
by another in any piece of work or watching; also, a turn at work which
is carried on by one person or gang relieving another; <as>as, a
<ex>spell</ex> at the pumps; a <ex>spell</ex> at the
masthead</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>spell</qex> at the wheel is called a trick.</q>
<rj><qau>Ham. Nav. Encyc.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The time during which one person or gang works until
relieved; hence, any relatively short period of time, whether a few
hours, days, or weeks.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nothing new has happened in this quarter, except the setting in of
a severe <qex>spell</qex> of cold weather.</q>
<rj><qau>Washington.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>One of two or more persons or gangs who work by
spells.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Their toil is so extreme that they can not endure it above four
hours in a day, but are succeeded by <qex>spells</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Garew.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A gratuitous helping forward of another's work;
<as>as, a logging <ex>spell</ex></as>.</def> <mark>[Local,
U.S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spell</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Spell
<hw>Spell</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos><ety>[AS. <ets>spell</ets> a
saying, tale, speech; akin to OS. & OHG. <ets>spel</ets>, Icel.
<ets>spjall</ets>,Goth. <ets>spill</ets>. Cf. <er>Gospel</er>,
<er>Spell</er> to tell the letters of.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A story;
a tale.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Hearken to my
<xex>spell</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A stanza, verse, or phrase supposed to be endowed
with magical power; an incantation; hence, any charm.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q> Start not; her actions shall be holy as⟦br⟧
You hear my <qex>spell</qex> is lawful.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spell</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Spell
<hw>Spell</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Spelled</conjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr> or <conjf>Spelt</conjf>
<pr>(<?/)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Spelling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>spellen</ets>,
<ets>spellien</ets>, tell, relate, AS. <ets>spellian</ets>, fr.
<ets>spell</ets> a saying, tale; akin to MHG. <ets>spellen</ets> to
relate, Goth. <ets>spill<?/n</ets>.e <er>Spell</er> a tale. In sense 4
and those following, OE. <ets>spellen</ets>, perhaps originally a
different word, and from or influenced by <ets>spell</ets> a splinter,
from the use of a piece of wood to point to the letters in schools: cf.
D. <ets>spellen</ets> to spell. Cf. <er>Spell</er> splinter.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To tell; to relate; to teach.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Might I that legend find,⟦br⟧
By fairies <qex>spelt</qex> in mystic rhymes.</q> <rj><qau>T.
Warton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To put under the influence of a spell; to affect by
a spell; to bewitch; to fascinate; to charm.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Spelled</xex> with words of power.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He was much <qex>spelled</qex> with Eleanor Talbot.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir G. Buck.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To constitute; to measure.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Saxon heptarchy, when seven kings put together did
<qex>spell</qex> but one in effect.</q> <rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To tell or name in their proper order letters of, as
a word; to write or print in order the letters of, esp. the proper
letters; to form, as words, by correct orthography.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The word ⟦ldquo⟧satire⟦rdquo⟧ ought to be <qex>spelled</qex> with
<it>i</it>, and not with <it>y</it>.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To discover by characters or marks; to read with
difficulty; -- usually with <xex>out</xex>; <as>as, to <ex>spell</ex>
out the sense of an author; to <ex>spell</ex> out a verse in the
Bible.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>spell</qex> out a God in the works of creation.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To sit <qex>spelling</qex> and observing divine justice upon every
accident.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spell</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Spell
<hw>Spell</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To form words with
letters, esp. with the proper letters, either orally or in
writing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When what small knowledge was, in them did dwell,⟦br⟧
And he a god, who could but read or <qex>spell</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To study by noting characters; to gain knowledge or
learn the meaning of anything, by study.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Where I may sit and rightly <qex>spell</qex>⟦br⟧
Of every star that heaven doth shew,⟦br⟧
And every herb that sips the dew.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spellable</ent>⟦br⟧
